misc: The station and the suburb it serves are named after Alphington, located in Devon, England.

misc: It was originally named Aspendale Park Racecourse, recieving its current name on the 1st of August 1905.
The station and the suburb it serves are named after Aspen, a race-winning mare owned by James Crooke. Crooke purchased land east of the present-day station to build the former Aspendale Racecourse.
The station is due to be rebuilt by 2029 as part of the Level Crossing Removal Project.
It opened as Auburn Road, before being renamed to Auburn a few months later on the 1st of September 1882.
It was named after two nearby residences that were built in the 1850s: Auburn Lodge amd Auburn House.

It was originally built with 2 side platforms. A new platform (platform 1) when a third line was constructed between Hawthorn and Campberwell in 1963, resulting in platforms 1 and 2 becoming an island platform.

Like the suburb it serves, the station is named after the Battle of Balaclava, which was fought by English, French and Turkish forces to capture the Russian Black Sea naval base of Sevastopol on the 25th of October 1854.

In October 2014, upgrades on the station were completed. Upgrades included the station now being staffed from first to last train eachh day, widening the platforms, improving stair and ramp access, signage, booking office facilities. waiting room, wheelchair shelters and toilets. There were also many additions: new station canopies, CCTV and space for future lifts.
It was closed for just over a decade between the 13th of July 1903 and the 1st of October 1914.

The station was originally known as Bell Park, before being to renamed Batman (named after John Batman) upon its 1914 reopening. John Batman is known for taking advantage of and leading massacres of Aboriginal people, as well as founding modern Melbourne.
A siding was to the former Lincoln Mills knitting works on Gaffney Street was constructed in 1920. It was later abolished in 1970.
There is a disused signal box on the up end of the station, which was built in 1935.

misc: It was originally known as Mornington Junction. It was renamed Baxter on the 6th of May 1918 after Captain John Baxter, a local proprietor of the nearby Carrup Carrup pastoral run.

Baxter was formerly the junction for the Mornington line, which was closed in 1981. Most of the Mornington line has since reopened as a tourist railway thanks to the efforts of the Mornington Railway Preservation Society.
It was named after Bayswater House, a property owned by bookmaker and publisher James John Miller. The property itself was named after Miller's birthplace in London.
The station was known as Macaulay (after a nearby post office) during construction, although this was changed to Bayswater by the time the station initially opened.

A train maintenance centre and stabling facilities opened adjacent to the station in April 1998, as part of the replacement of Jolimont Yard. The centre is able to carry out bogie repair/replacement, as well as under-carriage and overhead work.
In late 2015, the station was rebuilt and two level crossings on either side of the station were removed as part of the Level Crossing Removal Project.

misc: It originally opened as Monbulk, being given its current name on the 21st of November 1904.

It was originally situated on the Upper Ferntree Gully - Gembrook narrow gauge line. The station in its current configuration was built further down the line than the original station and opened on the 19th of Feburary 1962, after the line had been converted to broad gauge and electrified.
It is located about 100m south of Belgrave (Puffing Billy) station, a separate station sharing it's name which is the start of the Puffing Billy heritage railway.
It is the terminus for trains on the Belgrave line.
It was originally known as Preston-Bell Street, being given its current name on the 1st of August 1905.
Bell gets is named after the nearby Bell Street, which in turn is named after Francis Bell, a landowner in Coburg who had a property called Bell Manor.
In 2022, the station was completely rebuilt and elevated as part of the Level Crossing Removal Project. Two level crossings were also removed.

misc: It was originally known as East Brighton, being renamed Bentleigh after former Victorian Premier Thomas Bent on the 1st of May 1907.
The station had a pedestrian underpass installed in June 1987. It was filled in roughly 11 years later in 1998.

in 2006, VicTrack used the station's former pedestrian crossing to trial new technology designed to warn pedestrians of passing trains. This included an LED light box saying 'Another Train Coming' that would be lit if a train is approaching another train or if an express service was about to pass through.
Between the 4th of June and 28th of August 2016, the station was closed and rebuilt as part of the Level Crossing Removal Project. The nearby Centre Road level crossing was also removed.

misc: Its name was decided by the Victorian Railways Commissioners, following a referendum to decide on a name. Other potential names included Bondi, Heathdale, Bonheath, Baybeach and Bayside.

The station has been rebuilt twice: In 1981 when the former ground level station buildings were rebuilt, and in 2021 when the station was demolished and rebuilt in a trench as part of the level crossing removal project.
The former ground level station featured in the sitcom Kath and Kim (episode 2, series 4).
It is named after Boronia, a genus of roughly 160 flowering plantss. The name was suggested by local councillor Albert Chandler, who grew boronia plants in a nursery he owned nearby.
It originally opened with a single platform, with a second one being provided along with the duplication of the line between Bayswater and Ferntree Gully in 1957.

In 1998, the station was demolished and rebuilt in a trench as part of a grade separation project to remove the nearby Boronia Road level crossing. The new station opened on the 5th of November of the same year.

A $60 million upgrade was promised for Boronia by the labor government during the 2022 state election. The upgrade would consist of decking over the station to create new open space, building/platform/accessibility upgrades, CCTV and more.

misc: It is named after Box Hill in Surrey, England.
When the station opened, the suburb of Box Hill was a separate town from Melbourne with only several hundred residents.

In 1983, construction of a rebuilt station below ground level commenced - this was done to to remove the Station Street level crossing located on the down end of the station. Box Hill Shopping Centre and a bus terminus were built on top of the new station, with construction being completed in 1985.
Although it has 4 platforms, platform 1 has not been in use since June 1984, lacking both track and lighting.
The triple track section of the Belgrave/Lilydale line merges into two just beyond the down end of the station.
